The Way to Nuclear Disarmament
NEW YORK – Mass destruction weapons and disarmament pose one of the most challenging tasks that the world currently faces. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote global welfare and find solutions for problems that know no borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is of supreme importance as a common good.
My interest in this topic is partly based on personal experiences.
My home country, South Korea, has suffered from the devastation of conventional warfare and was exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other mass destruction weapons.
Doch gibt es derartige Bedrohungsszenarien selbstverständlich nicht nur in Asien.
Obwohl der Einsatz von Atomwaffen seit langem als Tabu gilt, bleibt die Abrüstung lediglich eine Bestrebung.
Ist nun ein Tabu, das sich bloß auf den Einsatz solcher Waffen bezieht, überhaupt ausreichend?
Wenn es um Kernwaffen geht, treffen Einzelstaaten die wichtigsten Entscheidungen.
Doch spielt die UNO eine entscheidende Rolle dabei.
We offer a central forum where states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and educate to achieve our agreed-upon goals and advocate for them.
The majority of states have decided to abandon nuclear weapons and have summarized their obligations under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
However, some states view such weapons as status symbols, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against an attack with nuclear weapons, which largely explains the estimated 26,000 still existing weapons.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and creating new risks that nuclear weapons may be used.
The world remains concerned about North Korea and Iran's nuclear activities, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns through peaceful means.
There are also concerns that we may be facing a "nuclear renaissance," as nuclear energy is increasingly seen as a clean energy alternative in times of growing climate change mitigation efforts.
The main concern is that this could lead to the production and use of more nuclear material that must be protected against proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are enormous.
Yet, the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Let us consider the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm International Peace Research Institute), military spending rose last year to over $1.3 trillion.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating that the total cost of nuclear weapons alone in the United States exceeded $58 billion, including future decommissioning costs.
This is, by any definition, a huge investment that could have been directed towards many other productive purposes.
Reflections on the costs of nuclear weapons and the dangers they pose have sparked a global ideas revolution, breathing new life into the concept of nuclear disarmament.
We have experienced the UN Arms Control Commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition, and Norway's Seven Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan established the International Commission on Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Civil society groups and states with nuclear weapons have also made proposals, such as the Hoover Plan, introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own Five-Point Plan.
Firstly: I call on all parties to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, particularly the nuclear powers, to fulfill their obligations under the treaty and to engage in negotiations for effective measures that lead to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate an arms convention supported by a strong monitoring system, as has been proposed for a long time in the UN.
I have circulated a draft of such a convention, which provides a good starting point, to all UN member states.
The nuclear powers should engage actively on this topic together with other states at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, the only multilateral disarmament negotiation forum in the world.
The world would also welcome a resumption of bilateral negotiations between the USA and Russia aimed at significantly and verifiably reducing their armaments.
The governments should also invest more in control research and development.
The proposal of the United Kingdom for a conference of nuclear powers on the topic of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should start discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could make it clear to the states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not be victims of a nuclear weapons attack or threatened by such an attack.
The Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the Nuclear Weapons Ban Treaty should stop their nuclear weapons programs and enter into their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoriums on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials may only be allowed to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to bring the Nuclear Test Ban Treaty into force, as well as impetus for the Conference on Disarmament to immediately and without preconditions take up discussions on a treaty concerning fissile materials.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly advocate for efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
In addition, I urge all parties to the Nuclear Weapons Ban Treaty to conclude security arrangements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily adopt the more stringent safety clauses of the Additional Protocol.
Viertens: Die Atommächte bringen häufig Beschreibungen in Umlauf, was sie unternehmen, um diese Ziele zu erreichen.
Doch erreichen diese Berichte selten die Öffentlichkeit.
Ich möchte die Atommächte bitten, derartige Materialien an das UN-Sekretariat zu senden und zu ihrer weiteren Verbreitung beizutragen.
Die Tatsache, dass es keine maßgebliche Schätzung der Gesamtanzahl von Atomwaffen gibt, bestätigt die Notwendigkeit größerer Transparenz.
Und schließlich sind verschiedene ergänzende Maßnahmen erforderlich.
Therefore, it includes the elimination of other types of weapons of mass destruction, new efforts against weapons of mass destruction terrorism, a limitation of the production and trade in conventional weapons, and new weapon bans, including for rockets and space weapons.
If there are real, verified progress in disarmament, the ability to eliminate the atomic threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the world's most deadly weapons and their components, we make it more difficult to carry out terrorist attacks with weapons of mass destruction.
These proposals offer a new beginning not only for disarmament but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
